post_text:
FYI ... The Sandy Segal Youth Health Center, located on the campus of Culver City High School and Culver City Middle School, is continuing to offer quality, affordable critical care even though the building is currently closed due to the pandemic.

Culver City students 12 to 18 years of age can obtain physical and mental health services, including but not limited to, routine physical exams, vision and hearing tests, immunizations, care management for chronic diseases, screening and management of depression, eating disorders, substance abuse, and domestic violence. Support groups led by social workers address a variety of topics related to stress, violence, suicide, substance abuse and bullying. For more information on the services offered by the Sandy Segal Youth Health Center, please click here: https://files.constantcontact.com/1a9e6620601/524a7a31-fc6b-42ac-a8ec-1aa13cebf571.pdf

Contact information for appointments is (310) 664-7788 for physical health concerns, and (310) 664-7437 for mental health services.

When: Thursday, July 16, 2020 11 AM ‚Äì 4 PM
Where: Culver City Fire Station 1, 9600 Culver Blvd.

Make your lifesaving blood donation appointment online now.

UCLA Blood & Platelet Center (BPC) is an AABB-Accredited Blood Donor Center with the focus on Donor Safety First. UCLA follows the highest standards of safety and infection control. To ensure optimal safety during the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, social distancing measures and increased infection control protocols have been implemented. Donors will be required to wear a face covering or mask while giving blood.

The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer program, or P-EBT, is designed for students who are normally able to get free or reduced price school meals to continue to receive those benefits during the pandemic. Apply and get up to $365 per child to spend on groceries.

Children may continue to receive "grab n go" meals or emergency food at COVID-19 emergency feeding sites offered by schools and community locations, even if they are receiving P-EBT benefits.

The P-EBT Card application deadline has been extended to July 15, 2020! If you are eligible and have NOT received an P-EBT card for your child(ren), learn more or apply at www.ca.p-ebt.org

AVPA‚Äôs Virtual Java Gala 2020 Friday, June 5, 7pm, streaming online

For the first time since the inception of AVPA in 1996, there won‚Äôt be a live ‚ÄúJava‚Äù production to celebrate the end of the school year. After 13 ‚ÄúJava Drama‚Äù shows and 11 ‚ÄúJava Gala‚Äù productions, AVPA will present the first Virtual ‚ÄúJava‚Äù ‚Äì JAVA GALA 2020!

The livestream show will showcase the creative work students have been producing while in quarantine. ‚ÄúThough we may not have been able to collaborate in person‚Äù said Tony Spano, AVPA‚Äôs executive director and creative director of music, ‚Äúwe‚Äôve been Zooming, rehearsing, recording, and creating our work within each department and finding ways to work across subjects.‚Äù

For more information, visit www.avpa.org

James Kocher will be majoring in music in the fall at UC ‚Äì Berkeley. James was involved with AVPA and said he will always remember, "the good (doing a great solo) and the bad (breaking the bass drum) ‚Äì things that happened to me during music concerts." He said he learned the most for AVPA's co-executive director, music teacher Dr. Tony Spano. "Dr. Spano taught me the most by giving me responsibilities, a group to contribute to, and an art form to study over the course of my four years." James encouraged freshmen to get iinvolved. "Don't wait," he said. "My biggest regret in middle school was not getting involved in theater in sixth grade, so in ninth grade, I went all in in music and I'm glad I did." James said his senior year was all about, "opportunity, growth and persistence" and added, "I will continue to wear all orange every Thursday. Don't worry." Good luck, James!

Brooklynn Hamilton is off to the Big Easy and Tulane University to study public health on the pre-med track. She said, "High school went by faster than I thought, so if you're still there, make the most of it!" Brooklynn played varsity soccer and was involved with ASB and Link Crew during her time at CCHS. She said her proudest accomplishment was, "maintaining my grades so that I could have my ideal college experience" and added that she will always remember, "the great friendships I've gained in my four years here." Brooklyn said her senior year was "gone too soon" and wanted to make sure incoming freshmen heeded this advice: "Don't procrastinate and keep your grades up. Make sure to take advantage of the resources we have at school. Create relationships with your teachers and counselors!" Some great nuggets of wisdom there, for sure! Best of luck, Brooklynn!

Leah Clark will be studying at Pasadena City College in the fall and said she has enjoyed her time at CCHS. "Culver City High School was definitely not what I expected coming into high school, but in a good way," she said. "I made lots of great memories with some good peoples!" Leah competed in track and field and served on the sports medicine team and as the football team manager. "I will always remember how much I loved working with the football team," she said. Leah had this advice for incoming freshmen: "Be true to yourself! It‚Äôs so important for you to stand your ground and not let people make you feel like less of a person because you aren‚Äôt doing what everyone else is doing." She said the teacher from whom she learned the most was Dr. Carlos Valverde. "Although I had him my last year, he has opened my eyes to so many issues that our society faces still, from racism to sexism to homophobia," she said. "I‚Äôve always been aware of these issues but it was so eye opening to learn about them in depth. TAKE ICL!!" Leah, best of luck in all you do!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR PROFILE ...

Aja Burslem is headed to Stanford University, where she plans to major in sociology and ultimately pursue law school. Her advice to incoming freshmen is to, "Become as involved as you can in the areas you are passionate about, whatever they may be. CCHS has so many opportunities for you to explore; you don't need to have it all figured out from the beginning! Work hard, trust the process, and don't forget to treasure each moment because it's truly over before you know it. Also, don't procrastinate." At Culver, Aja served as an Office of Child Development intern at La Ballona and was involved in Best Buddies and Ballona Creek Renaissance, and was a member of volleyball team. She said she will always remember, "the incredible memories I've made with my best friends and all of the supportive teachers and staff I've had the chance to learn from." Good luck in Palo Alto, Aja!

Sophie Little, who played outfield and second base for the Lady Centaurs, recently signed her commitment to play softball at Westccliff University.

Little will be part of the inaugural Warriors softball team. Westcliff will enter its third year of athletic competition when the NAIA 2020-2021 season begins in the fall. The Warriors will expand their athletic department to 12 sports, with tennis, swimming and dive, surf, softball and cheer joining current programs men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs basketball, baseball, men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs volleyball, beach volleyball, cross country, track & field and men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs soccer.

Westcliff, a private university in Irvine, will play in the California Pacific Conference.

CONGRATULATIONS SOPHIE! #culverpride

post_text: Bienvenidos a Culver City Adult School's long-awaited "Spanish for the Workplace" class! This is a conversation-based six-week course via live, or virtual, or both. Students will be able to learn useful Spanish language vocabulary and phrases and build confidence in using Spanish to serve Spanish-speaking patrons, parents, and patients! Ana Gonzalez will be studying at California State University ‚Äì Long Beach in the fall and said she will always remember, "sitting at the senior lawn soaking up the sun with my friends." She was involved with ASB, Best Buddies, BCR and played volleyball. She said her proudest moment at CCHS was on the court, "winning CIF and getting a ring." Since her freshman year, Ana said she has, "grown and gathered a circle of friends that are more likely family to me now and I know I will have them for life!" Good luck in all you do, Ana!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR PROFILE ...

Jade Ravare will be attending Xavier University of Louisiana and studying Pre-Medical Psychology. She was President of Future Entrepreneurs and involved with Link Crew, Sports Training and Black Student Union during her time at CCHS. Her advice to new Culver student is, "Don't be afraid to reach out to your Link Crew Leaders; they are there to support you. I spoke to my Link Crew Leaders the day of Freshman Orientation, and that was it. After I became a Link Crew leader and had freshmen come up to me and tell me how my advice helped them, I realized I could have used some advice during my first year of high school as well. Don't deprive yourself of help, especially when the resources are right in front of you." Jade said her proudest accomplishment in high school was, "Raising money for calculators that are now in the school library." Here's hoping your future is bright as the sun, Jade!

Bella Jimenez will be going to work after graduation and hopes to attend college in the future to study chemistry or nursing. She said the CCHS teacher who taught her the most was Dr. Pernoon. "He was really preparing us for college," she said. "He would tell us that when we write our papers it'll be much harder because the professor will hope/assume that we know how to write an essay." Bella was involved with ASL Club and Girl's Pact Club at Culver and said she will always remember, "the good times I had with my friends." Looking ahead, Bella said, "I can't wait for what my future may hold for me." Neither can we! Best of luck Bella!

post_text:
CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR PROFILE ...

Charlie Kayem will be in Sweden this fall doing online learning from Santa Monica College. She said high school has helped her be more outgoing. "I have come out of my shell, and been able to find myself," she said. "I also used to be very shy, but I have become more open to being vulnerable, which allowed me to truly be myself." During her time as a Centaur, Charlie served as freshman class president, played varsity soccer and was involved with link crew, prime time, STAND and WE charity. She said she will always remember, "My friends who made my high school, and the love and happiness that I was surrounded by." She credits art teacher Craig Wisner with teaching her the most. "Not only did he teach me how to make bowls, he made me think deeper about life," she said. "He opened up my mind to different meanings in life, which I genuinely appreciate." Best of luck in your future, Charlie!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR PROFILE ...

Alexander Tesfa-Mariam will be going to work and plans to ultimately attend college in the future. He said he was glad to have the guidance of Julian Torrez. "He introduced me to AVPA theater and allowed me the opportunity to fall in love with the department and its inhabitants," she said. "I also can't forget that it was thanks to him that I found people who I will stay friends with for much longer than high school." Alexander's advice is to, "Be yourself, no matter how scary that might seem. The reward for your bravery will be worth it. The reward is more than friends, it's a family." Involved in AVPA theater, tennis and CCC Ambassadors, he said his proudest accomplishment was finishing AP Chemistry. He would tell incoming freshmen: "You will only be able to experience high school once, so don't be held back by fear, or else you will find yourself not living at all. It has taken me three years to break out of my shell, I hope you break out of yours sooner." Here's wishing you all the best in your future, Alexander!

Madison Qui√±ones will be attending Aveda Institute Los Angeles in the fall. "The best piece of advice that I could give to a freshman would be to branch out and make friends," she said. "Since I was new to the district, that was the first move I made, which has led me to sharing some super memorable experiences with some really special people." She enjoyed volunteering and participating in beach clean-ups. "My proudest high school accomplishment was finally being comfortable enough with myself to choose my own future," she said. "My sister went to a four-year college, which is what I thought I needed to do. I realized shortly after turning in my college applications that it wasn‚Äôt the route I wanted to go down. Opening my eyes to the world of cosmetology and being taught all things hair and makeup for my career is everything I‚Äôve wanted and more." Here's wishing you all the best for a fantastic future, Madison!

Madison Jensen will be attending Santa Monica College in the fall and said her proudest moments were as a student-athlete, being able to represent Culver City in three different sports: equestrian team, girls volleyball and girls water polo. She said, "the athletic community at CCHS has taught me what it's like to be part of one big family." She said she will always remember traveling with the cheer team to take pictures at the away games for football. "I didn't miss a single game this last season." Madison said that since being a freshman, she has a different outlook on life. "As seniors, our lives seem to hold more meaning," she said. "We can appreciate the good little things and worry less about the bad little things." Best of luck, Madison!

Rafael Marquez will be attending Santa Monica College in the fall and said he is grateful for his girlfriend. "My girlfriend taught me the true meaning of having friends and knowing your worth and that there‚Äôs always one person that would hold your hand through anything and everything. I hate that I have to leave her to go onto college. She has taught me so much about who is your true friend and who‚Äôs just around for the attention; and she‚Äôs helped me through so much through my high school career and has always kept me in check and out of trouble." A varsity football player, Rafael called his time at CCHS "simply best time of my life." He encouraged freshmen to, "please don‚Äôt be rude to teachers. The application period for the Children's Defense Fund's Beat the Odds program will be open for another three weeks. Please help spread the word to eligible freshman students. Applicants must:

‚Ä¢ be a high school freshman
‚Ä¢ demonstrate commitment to their education
‚Ä¢ demonstrate commitment to their community
‚Ä¢ demonstrate need for support
‚Ä¢ reside in Los Angeles County

Selected honorees will receive a $10,000 scholarship and have access to a suite of academic and career readiness opportunities, as well as leadership and life skills development to support them as they transition from high school to college and beyond.

The application period will close at 11:59 p.m. on Sunday, May 31, 2020. Visit CDF online to apply and learn more about the CDF Beat the Odds program and the organization.

Best of luck as you pursue your dreams, Savannah!

Giulianna Pineda is headed to American Career College to pursue her goal of becoming a medical assistant. She would tell incoming freshmen, "Don‚Äôt stop! The sky's the limit!" She said she was excited to complete her final year at CCHS, a year she called "Nostalgic, Different, and Uncertain." Best of luck in following your dreams, Giulianna!

post_text:
CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Selena Andrade is planning to attend West LA College in the fall and then transfer to the University Of Oregon. As an athletic trainer in the CCHS Sports Medicine program, she said her fondest memories are, "training for every Friday Night Football game." Selena said the best piece of advice she can give to incoming freshmen is to, "Be yourself, enjoy high school and live your life to the fullest." Best of luck on your journey, Selena!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Annie Melnick is heading north to the University of Washington, where she will major in English. "During freshman year, I always set unrealistic expectations for myself," she said. "Throughout my four years at Culver, I realized things don't always go as planned, and that's okay. I learned how to adapt to change and succeed because of it." Annie was involved in AVPA Theatre, Yearbook, Girls Build, the Feminism Club, and she said she will always remember, "my unique experiences and my amazing friends." She said would describe her senior year as, "Unexpected, Fulfilling, and Unforgettable." Here's hoping you have an unforgettable college experience as well!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Victor Antonio Urrutia will be headed to community college in the fall and described his senior year as, "Weird, Stressful and Fun." Active in Latinos unidos and after school care, Victor said he most appreciated the teachers who didn't give up on him and staff in the library. High school, he said, has made him, "just a bit smarter" and given him, "a lot of passion for what I want to do." His advice to the incoming freshman class is, "Don't automatically give up when times are hard ‚Äì try a lil'!" Victor keep on trying and best of luck in the future!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Collin Dixson is headed to Cal State Long Beach as a history major in the fall. He said his proudest accomplishment at CCHS was, "earning athletic scholar awards for football and track." Collin's advice to incoming freshmen is to, "start out being focused on your grades in your freshman year and never become complacent." He is especially thankful for, "Ms. (Jennifer) Kochevar, who taught me a lot about U.S. history, especially the Civil Rights Movement." Best of luck in all you do, Collin!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Ivan Paul Sanchez is headed off to serve in the National Guard after graduation. Ivan said his friends taught him a lot during his days at CCHS ‚Äì " taught me how to be sociable, 'cause I use to be an introvert." He said his best advice for incoming freshmen is to, "be yourself and don't be scared to ask for help and seek true friends that will guide you." Like many seniors, he said he will always have lasting memories of this quarantine. Ivan, best of luck in the future, and thank you for your future service to our country!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Giuliana Castro is heading to Santa Monica College in the fall and enjoyed spending much of her time at CCHS in the pool, including an opportunity to train at the Olympic Training Center in Colorado Springs her junior year. "I have been a competitive swimmer for the past 11 years, swimming has really helped me to become more disciplined and hardworking which are things I will be able to carry into college. I plan on transferring to a four-year university from SMC, where I plan to major in psychology." She said she will always remember walking with her sister on the bridge to school. She has, perhaps, the best advice of all, "Listen to your mother!" and calls her mom the person from whom she has learned the most. "At the end of the four years, I finally realized she was right." Good luck in all you do Giuliana and keep on listening to Mom!

Drew Nosike is off to community college and work as a Santa Monica lifeguard after graduation. Drew said he will always remember "Mr. (Ehsaan) Mesaghali in architecture" and competing in the Skills USA Competition, competitive events showcasing the best career and technical education students in the nation. Drew said he gained maturity during his time at CCHS and added that he enjoyed helping in beach clean-up efforts. His advice for incoming freshmen is to, "Walk on the right side of the hallway." Best of luck wherever your walks take you in the future, Drew!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Sierra Chabola is headed to San Diego State University to study kinesiology in the fall. During her time at CCHS, she played tennis, soccer, and lacrosse and participated in Link Crew and A+A. Sierra said her greatest accomplishment was "getting to the state championship with my soccer team." Sierra said that, thanks to Culver City High School, "I've developed essential life skills and learned the extent of my mental strength." Sierra said she is thankful for math teacher Chloe Park. "Ms. Park taught me how to live life to the fullest and love what you do." Best of luck in all that you do, Sierra!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Valerie Gonzalez will be a Colorado State University Ram in the fall. During her time at Culver, she was involved with yearbook and served as a CCC Ambassador. Her advice for incoming freshman is to, "Ask for help whether it be friends, teachers, staff. There will always be somebody that can help you, even if you feel isolated." Valerie said high school has helped her become more comfortable in her own skin and added that she will always remember, "the moments in which my peers made me laugh through hard days." Good luck, Valerie!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Taylor Albertson will be attending the University of Northern Iowa in the fall. She said, "The person who taught me the most in high school was Ms.(Melanie) De Armond because she taught me the most important thing which was that I was capable of being loved. Ms.De Armond was the first person who truly made me feel like I mattered and everyday that I spent with her she made me feel unconditionally loved. Throughout my high school education she taught me some of the most important things about life like how to get by in the adult world, the importance of college, the importance of happiness, and the importance of self care. Ms.De Armond is an amazing person who taught me amazing things and I am so thankful that I have her in my life. She was what made high school truly great for me!" Taylor was involved with Link Crew, academic mentoring, and AVPA film during her time at CCHS, and we wish her well as a Panther!

post_text:
May 4-8 is Teacher Appreciation Week!

We want to celebrate ALL of our teachers, especially during this most challenging time in their teaching careers. Calling all CCUSD students and families to get creative and show our teachers some love. Draw or paint a picture. Write a song. Photograph something. Do an interpretive dance. Perform a skit. Write a poem. Animate a scene. Create any type of art that celebrates our teachers during this time.

Note: We prefer a collective celebration message instead of singling out any individual teachers.

Submit your teacher appreciation artwork to heathermoses@ccusd.org by noon on Friday, May 1. We will share our collective creation with the CCUSD community the week of May 4. Thank you in advance for your participation.

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Savannah House was one of only 12 students in the state to qualify for the California State Speech and Debate Competition as a Presiding Officer in Congress in both 2019 and 2020. "I competed in 2019, and sadly, the competition was cancelled in 2020," she said. Savannah is heading off to Hanover College in the fall and said her dad taught her more than anyone during her high school years. "He was the one who pushed me to do all the activities that I love to do now and told me that at the end of the day, I should do the things that are fun to me," she said. "He always tells me, 'If you really want to do something, you will fine the time and make it happen.' At first, that seemed intimidating, but then I realized that he was right; now is the time to not give any opportunities up because you never know what may come out of them." Best of luck for a fantastic future!

Councilmember Mike Bonin
April 24 at 11:00 AM ¬∑

Metro Los Angeles is hosting a contest to ask residents to help name the two machines that will be responsible for digging tunnels from the VA hospital campus in West LA to Westwood/UCLA on the Westside for the Purple Line Extension Transit Project-- a huge part of my #westsidefastforward initiative.

Metro‚Äôs machine naming contest has two parts. The first contest is to name the machines and is open to U.S. Veterans affiliates (veterans and VA employees) and UCLA affiliates (university employees, students and alumni). The second part of the contest is an art competition that is open to all Los Angeles County residents who will compete to illustrate their ideal community on the Purple Line Extension route.

Read more about the contest and how you can participate at the link below.

https://thesource.metro.net/2020/04/20/art-and-name-submissions-open-for-purple-line-extension-transit-project-section-3-tunnel-boring-machines/

Lena-Louise Moores will be off to Santa Monica College in the fall, but said she will always remember, "all of the amazing memories my friends and I have made from middle school to now. We have grown so close and stood by one another through everything." Lena-Louise was involved in volleyball, Best Buddies, and Ballona Creek Renaissance; and said her greatest high school accomplishment was, "Always staying true to who I am and what I‚Äôm passionate about." She added, "I‚Äôve learned that life is never easy, and it will throw you curve balls. But you must persevere because you never know what good can come out of it." Good luck at SMC!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Kacey Oschack is off to study at Cal-State Chico in the fall and said, "Quarantine has really been horrible overall, but I am so proud of all the seniors who have stuck it through and have stayed strong. I know there will be some good coming our way soon!" Involved in AVPA Theatre, Kacey said performing as as Velma Kelly, one of her dream roles, in "Chicago" was the highlight of her year. "My best piece of advice is to try everything. Don't be scared to ever be yourself or do things you enjoy. Also, don't worry if you start to become less close with your current friends. That happens naturally and you will make more that have similar interests to you." Kacey said she learned a great deal from her director. "Lee Hanson has taught me the most in high school. Not only has she taught me so much about theatre and how to succeed in that business but also how to respect people, even if you do not get along with them, and overall how to be a good person." Best of luck at Cal-State Chico!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Gabriela Garcia Ceniseros is off to Santa Monica College in the fall and said she will bring with her the things teacher Marcos White taught her in his Health, Sports Therapy, and Sports Medicine classes. "In his class, I didn't just learn muscles, bones, and to properly disinfect and bandage a wound. I also learned to create a resume, how to look and how to act in an interview. He taught us to be successful in his class but also to be successful in life. He is a good person, who deserves the credit." Gabriela has been involved in many clubs; Marvel Club, Girls Who Code, Best Buddies, SFMV Club. She was also a student athletic trainer for the Centaur Cross Country and Football teams for a short time. She said she will always remember her "amazing friends, dedicated teachers, and the wonderful staff of Culver City High School. They will always be a treasured memory of my high school experience." Good luck, Gabriela!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Estrella Espinal Canizales is heading to community college in the fall and said a lot has changed during her time at CCHS. "I think I've changed a lot since freshman year. Academically, I've improved so much that I even surprised myself. Also, I've socialized a lot more and have made many great friends over the years, and I'm doing things now that my freshman self would have never thought about doing. It's just crazy because people say that, ‚ÄúOh, I'm never gonna change‚Äù but honestly high school does change you for the better or worse." Her advice to future students is to, "just try your best, because trying is better than doing nothing and that can lead you to many opportunities in the future." Good luck in all your future opportunities!

It‚Äôs so important for you to stand your ground and not let people make you feel like less of a person because you aren‚Äôt doing what everyone else is doing." Best of luck doing exactly what you want to do in the future, Caleb!

post_text:
CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Ana Carolina Quintanilha is headed for community college in the fall. She said she learned a lot at CCHS. "I have learned who I am and what I want. I went from an extremely shy girl who was scared to make friends to becoming one of the water polo varsity captains. I used to play the sport my dad loved, until sophomore year when I encountered my passion, my sport, what makes me happy. I‚Äôm definitely more healthy, and in shape than I was freshman year. I‚Äôve become outgoing, and not afraid of challenges. I‚Äôve lost a lot a long the way, but senior year awarded me for all the hard work I put in these past four years." Ana became a fluent English speaker during her time as a Centaur and said her coaches truly impacted her. "Nestor Dordoni and Cristobal Navlag taught me how to be a team player, in and outside of the field. They taught me how to let people in and enjoy every second of what I‚Äôm doing. Living in the moment, game by game." Best of luck, Ana!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Alexandra (Sasha) Holland, an outstanding student-athlete, is on her way to UC, Santa Cruz, and she expressed what seniors across the country are feeling: "I am an AP/honors student who has worked very hard over the years, and I‚Äôm very sad that senior year was cut short." Sasha, who also ran track, said he proudest moment was on the court "winning Ocean League and CIF with my volleyball team." During her days at CCHS, she learned lessons that will last her entire life. "I became more mature and realized the importance of making memories with friends, while not straying away from doing my best in school." Best of luck to the newest Banana Slug!

Rodney Farrow will be an Arizona State University Sun Devil come the fall. Amazingly, he had perfect attendance during his time at CCHS!! Involved in Black Student Union and ASB, he said teacher and Director of Student Activities Carlos Valverde taught him the most. "He taught all of his students to make sure they have a plan for the future, and focus on yourself." Rodney added that his advice for incoming freshmen is, "to focus on yourself and find good friends that will help you along the way with school, and be the best of friends with your counselor." Good luck in Tempe!

CLASS OF 2020 SENIOR SALUTE ...

Natalie Glassman will be a UCLA Bruin in the fall. She said, "My friends and teachers have taught me the most. I learned from them to have confidence in myself, that mistakes are essential in order to grow, and that often the best results come from stepping outside of my comfort zone." Involved in CHLA Junior Ambassadors Club, the Feminism Club, Chirons, and tennis, Natalie said her proudest accomplishment in high school was "my work as a Chiron. Forming connections with my mentees and helping them realize that they can succeed has been extremely rewarding and is something I will never forget." Best of luck Natalie!

We have received many requests for more distribution of Chromebook devices for students to use for distance learning. We did have more people than expected at last Monday‚Äôs distribution so we are planning more distributions going forward. We are working on a plan to do them either by appointment or in limited groups and will share those plans as soon as we are ready. We will also handle replacing problem devices during the same times as new distributions.

For those who already have devices, please email TechHelp@ccusd.org if you need any support.

Thank you for your patience, we are working as quickly as possible to get everyone what they need.

post_text: During the early signing period for NCAA football, Culver City High School had two outstanding athletes sign with Division 1 programs. Corner and slot receiver Khary Crump signed with the University of Arizona, and wide receiver and defensive back Chris Miller signed with Sacramento State. In the more recent late signing period, wide receiver Tanner Duve was offered a grant-in-aid to the University of Pennsylvania of the Ivy League, and offensive lineman Blake Kneebone was offered a scholarship to the Colorado School of Mines.
shared_text:
CULVERCITYOBSERVER.COM
Four Centaurs Sign Football Scholarships
text:
During the early signing period for NCAA football, Culver City High School had two outstanding athletes sign with Division 1 programs. Corner and slot receiver Khary Crump signed with the University of Arizona, and wide receiver and defensive back Chris Miller signed with Sacramento State. In the more recent late signing period, wide receiver Tanner Duve was offered a grant-in-aid to the University of Pennsylvania of the Ivy League, and offensive lineman Blake Kneebone was offered a scholarship to the Colorado School of Mines.

Chicago is the longest-running American musical on Broadway with music by John Kander, lyrics by Fred Ebb, and book by Ebb and Bob Fosse. Set in Chicago in the jazz age, the musical is based on a 1926 play of the same name by reporter Maurine Dallas Watkins, about actual criminals and the crimes on which she reported. post_text:
Culver City Council PTA HSA Nominations

The Honorary Service Awards (HSA) are the annual awards given to those outstanding members of the community who have served our children in the community. This year, we are looking for stories, any stories, no matter how small of anyone you feel has done something special, even if only at one school, please share the story with us. Whether it be a parent, and administrator, or just a community member, as long as they served the children in some capacity.

We are seeking out those unsung heroes, those volunteers who work quietly, without complaint but are barely noticed or recognized. We are asking you, the community to help us find them. So share your stories, because someone else may also have a story about that very same person and you just don't know about it. We want to collect these stories and help find our unsung heroes.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSe6Evn7rzos-u8b1dK9n4gq-knOcvZlFjaxhWVKCrNNXkTmfw/viewform

Sincerely,

Leslie Lockhart, Superintendent

post_text:
FYI ... The following message was sent to all of our Middle School families:

Dear Culver City Middle School Community,

This week we have become deeply concerned about one of our teachers, Ms. Brianna Capillo, who has been missing since January 12. While her family works with authorities to locate her, we know that you will join us in sending our sincere thoughts for a safe and quick return to her family. Due to the ongoing nature of the search, there are few details that can be shared and we ask that you respect the privacy of Ms. Capillo‚Äôs family during this difficult time.

We will continue to work with Principal Villafranca and the Language Arts team to make sure Ms. Capillo‚Äôs classes are covered and that instruction continues as planned. In the case that your child has heard the news and is struggling, CCMS counselors will be available to offer support for our CCMS students.

If and when we find out more details, we will share as appropriate. For now, we send our support and prayers to Ms. Capillo‚Äôs family as they wait for her return.

Sincerely,

Leslie Lockhart, Superintendent

Casino Night is coming! On April 18, the Culver City High School Booster Club will turn Veteran's Auditorium into a FUNdraising casino. Over the past years, the club has raised just over $500,000 for student activities. Tickets will be on sale shortly.

Equally as important, if you have an item to donate for the auctions (CCHS Boosters is a 501c3), please email Casino.Night@LASlots.com. Help the club raise money while you get the word out about your business.

Looking forward to seeing everyone on April 18.

The CA Dashboard is LIVE: The Fall 2019 Accountability information is now available and accessible to the public.

The California School Dashboard provides parents and educators with meaningful information on school and district progress so they can participate in decisions to improve student learning.

To help parents and educators identify strengths and areas for improvement, California reports how districts, schools, and student groups are performing across state and local measures. For state measures, performance is based on two factors: current year results and whether those results improved from the prior year.

Please visit https://caschooldashboard.org/reports/19644440000000/2019 to view District and individual school indicators of performance.

Just email us at AskCCUSD@ccusd.org and we will make sure your question is routed to the correct person and that you get an answer quickly.

CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE

Breigh Dang

Miss Dang has shown tremendous initiative in restructuring the purpose of homework in her El Rincon classroom. Through deep professional reflections and discussions, she has redefined the purpose of homework for her students and families. She stands behind the current research and has helped her classroom families to step outside of the traditional "box" of assigning homework in exchange for a fresh perspective. Now, students engage in math and reading projects to think more deeply in those content areas, and to have more time spent with their families at home. I appreciate Miss Dang's courage!

Amy Thiel

As the school nurse, Amy makes every single student and parent feel as if they are getting the best possible care. She is so friendly to the students. She is extremely thorough making sure all her bases are hit and never seeming like it is too much. She has to keep up with so many students at schools with diabetes, constant calls giving Insulin numbers and emergency questions. Running back and forth to schools and always with a smile. Taking time to talk to parents.

Amy is simply the best!

post_text:
CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE

Elsy Villafranca

Ms. Villafranca is one of those educators who makes a difference not by just saying things, but by doing them. As principal of the diverse and ever-evolving beast that is Culver City Middle School, she is adept and thoughtful in her leadership as principal. When it comes to serving her students, she is constantly looking for what we as a school can do better to meet the needs of all of our student body. Whether it is providing better supports for our language learners, creating bigger challenges for our top performers, or finding ways to get every student intentionally involved academically and socially, Ms. Villafranca works tirelessly to make sure each panther feels at home at CCMS. As an educator, a colleague and as a friend Ms. Villafranca shines. CCUSD is lucky to have such a fantastic and hard working principal for our middle graders!

The Centaurs, a perfect 12-0, will have their hands full with Swordsmen, who have just a single blemish on their 11-1 record.

Let's have a great turnout and support the team!

CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE

Diana Fannon and Chris Cole

Today, we are proud to thank the incredible team of Diana and Chris!

They are a compassionate team who are helping redefine how special education looks in CCUSD. They are on the front line of bringing inclusive practices and Universal Design for Learning (UDL) to classrooms around the district. Their belief in the potential of all learners is shown by the respect and consideration they give every day to their students and families. They lead by example, and we‚Äôre lucky to have them.

Chris received a special nomination: "Mrs. Cole has worked tirelessly for over 25 years in the special ed department making the department run smoothly and trying to meet the diverse needs of all special ed students in the district. She works behind the scenes putting in late hours and weekends. She knows the special ed families and teachers intimately and is always available to all of us. I think she deserves a big thank you for all her work and devotion to Culver City schools."

Thank you to this incredible and dynamic duo!

CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE

Delmy Pineda

Comments from just two of the many people who truly appreciate Delmy's efforts in the El Rincon Elementary School cafeteria ...

Delmy has increased breakfast participation by encouraging the inclusion of second and third graders in our Second Chance Breakfast program during recess. It's working, and participation has increased by approximately 30 meals a day. Next step ‚Äì first grade!

Delmy runs a bright, clean, and welcoming kitchen at El Rincon. Students are greeted with her positive and kind presence, she knows and connects with the kids, and always has a smile on her face. The cafeteria is always decorated with welcoming pictures and signs, and everyone is excited to see what fruits and vegetables is in the salad bar. Thank you for making the cafeteria such an inviting place!

Thank you, Delmy, for all of your hard work!

post_text:
AVPA'S ART IN MOTION OPENS TONIGHT!

AVPA's Fall Dance Concert titled "Art In Motion" features both student and faculty works where choreographers were tasked with finding a piece of art to inspire their creations. The artwork(s) will be projected onstage during the dance performances, providing a backdrop as well as an extra layer of interest for the audience eyes. The evening will also feature students from the AVPA Art Department doing live art demonstrations inspired by the dancers they see onstage. An evening not to miss!

Performances will be held Thursday, Friday, and Saturday (November 21, 22, 23) at 7pm with a special matinee performance at 2pm on Saturday, November 23. All performances will be held at Robert Frost Auditorium.

*Performance running time is 60 minutes.
Tickets available at the door: $7 for adults, $5 for students.

Fallon Perdue-Smith

‚ÄúI am not a teacher, but an awakener‚Äù said American Poet laureate and Pulitzer Prize winner Robert Frost.

His message: Teachers can awaken a student‚Äôs belief in themselves. Frost encourages the idea of inspiring curiosity and sparking the desire for knowing in students, and some teachers simply get students curious about discovering knowledge for themselves. They focus on their interests and inherent skills and natural talents.

CCHS's Fallon Perdue-Smith is one of those special educators.

She goes above and beyond and does everything for her students to be the best they can be.

CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE:

Maria Espinoza

Ms. Maria is responsible for the lunch duty and after-school programs at Farragut. Her friendly, warm smile will greet all the kids and parents at school. There is a 15-minute window of transition between the end of the school day and after-school programming on Wednesdays, and Ms. Maria is running around making sure our kids are at the right location. She even makes sure the little ones get a chance to order their popsicles because there may be a long, chaotic line on those sale days.

She will not leave Farragut until she knows all the students have left with a responsible adult or sibling. We just love that she stays with our Farragut family after her son graduated years ago. We are lucky to have this wonderful educator on our campus!

CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE:

Ann Marie Ysaguirre

School libraries provide more than just books, computers and other technology and fun and educational activities. School libraries provide a safe haven for all students to think, create, share, and grow. But what truly makes libraries great are the individuals who run them. So, it is no surprise that Ann Marie Ysaguirre is making a difference in her school community at Linwood E. Howe.

"Our librarian is always going out of her way to provide not only books, but also guidance to our kids. She is by far the only staff who knows EVERY child at our school."

Thank you Ann Marie for all of your hard work and dedication!

The Culver City football team is the No. 1 ranked team in CIF Division V and will put its undefeated 10-0 record on the line when it opens the CIF playoffs tonight at 7p.m.

The Centaurs, led by dual-threat quarterback Zevi Eckhaus, have one of the most exciting offenses in the state and their defense is getting better each week.

Their first challenge in the CIF playoffs will be Bishop Diego of Santa Barbara at Culver City High School's Chabola Stadium.

Bishop Diego is 5-5 and are led by 6' 2" running back Adrian Socacco, who has 879 yards on 161 carries.

Let's get out there and cheer the Centaurs on to victory!
#culverpride
text:
The Culver City football team is the No. 1 ranked team in CIF Division V and will put its undefeated 10-0 record on the line when it opens the CIF playoffs tonight at 7p.m.

The Centaurs, led by dual-threat quarterback Zevi Eckhaus, have one of the most exciting offenses in the state and their defense is getting better each week.

Their first challenge in the CIF playoffs will be Bishop Diego of Santa Barbara at Culver City High School's Chabola Stadium.

Bishop Diego is 5-5 and are led by 6' 2" running back Adrian Socacco, who has 879 yards on 161 carries.

Let's get out there and cheer the Centaurs on to victory!
#culverpride

CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE:

Dr. Lisa Michel

Dr. Lisa Michel has been described as detail-oriented, thorough, and hard-working. Those who nominated her describe a work ethic that is unparalleled! As the Director of Secondary Curriculum and Instruction, Dr. Michel provides invaluable support to teachers and administrators at CCMS, CCHS, CPHS, and the Adult School. She has supported teaching staff in the development of rigorous goals to improve student outcomes, works with secondary math teachers to implement instructional practices that are grounded in research based best practices and which encourage and develop independent, critical thinking among students, and supports the Educational Services department with numerous initiatives including MTSS, CTE programming, Federal Programs Monitoring, and Professional Development. Thank you to Dr. Lisa Michel for exemplifying "educator - of all ages!"

BOARD WORKSHOP ON ACADEMIC DATA TOMORROW!

Once a month, CCUSD holds a board workshop, in which a special single topic is explored in depth. These workshops are less formal than the bi-weekly board meetings, and as with any board meeting, the public is invited to attend. On Tuesday, November 5, at 6:30 pm, at the District Office, the CCUSD Board of Education will hold a workshop focused on academic data, presenting the most current student achievement information about CCUSD. This is new data, based on the public release of state test scores, that will be used in determining CCUSD‚Äôs academic performance on the 2019 Dashboard.

The California School Dashboard contains important information on schools, districts, and county offices of education. It goes beyond test scores to provide a more complete picture of how schools and districts are meeting the needs of all students. We invite the community to join us on Tuesday for an interactive, deep dive into how CCUSD is meeting both the academic and social-emotional needs of its students.

CCUSD THANK AN EDUCATOR PROFILE:

Saira Sayeed

Ms. Sayeed has been a part of the La Ballona community for many years, having been a parent there as well as serving in her role as an Instructional Assistant. Nominated for Thank an Educator recognition, Ms. Sayeed was described as "kind, calm, and really, really smart!" Ms. Sayeed has worked with students of all grade levels at La Ballona Elementary School and she is known for her ability to help struggling students improve their math skills. Staff describe Ms. Sayeed as level headed, reliable, and an all around gift to have at the school. Parents feel the same. "If you have a Kindergarten student at La Ballona, you certainly know Ms. Sayeed's impact on children is positive and far reaching. My own child loved working with her and always told me how she was serious about work, but then had such a big smile when he got a concept she was helping him with." CCUSD is pleased to recognize the contributions of Ms. Saira Sayeed, and we say "Thank you!" for all that you do for our students.

Advisory from Culver City Police Department: Press Release: Attempt to Locate Missing Juvenile

Culver City Police Department
PRESS RELEASE
Scott Bixby, Chief of Police

Attempt to Locate Missing Person

FOR PRESS RELEASE

Last Seen: Tuesday, October 29th, 2019 at 11:45 AM

Location: Kayne Eras Center 5350 Machado Rd, Culver City CA

Description: Jerimiah Aaron Philips, male, 12 years old, 4‚Äô9‚Äù-5‚Äô0‚Äù tall, 125 lbs, short curly dark hair, brown eyes with a small scar on his left cheek bone

On 10/29/19 at approximately1145 hours, school staff saw Philips exit the campus through a gate onto Jefferson Blvd. School staff pursued Philips as he ran westbound on Jefferson Blvd towards Sepulveda Blvd and lost sight of him in the immediate area.

Philips suffers from mental health issues and has previously runaway. In the past, he has been located using the public transportation system. Philips is a resident of the city of Los Angeles.

If seen please call the Culver City Police Department Watch Commander‚Äôs Office at 310-253-6202.

post_text:
Should the High School Day Begin Later?
CCUSD Wants to Hear Your Thoughts

Over the last decade or more, scientific research has demonstrated that adolescents have difficulty falling asleep sleep before about 11 p.m., and need as much as nine hours of sleep per night.

In response, the American Medical Association recommended in 2016 that secondary schools begin the school day no earlier than 8:30 a.m. Some high schools that have changed to a later start time have reported initial improvements in both mental health and academic performance, although it is unclear at this time if that data is ongoing/sustained. Those sites have also had to address logistical issues to accomplish the change.

Here in California, Senate Bill 328, if passed, would require high school classes to start at 8:30 a.m. or later. CCUSD has initiated a survey to explore the idea of later start times at Culver City High School. This survey is a first step in gathering stakeholder input about this important issue.
